Absolutely, Shivam! Letâ€™s break down how Suspense and loading.tsx work in Next.js App Router, especially in the context of server-rendered pages and async operations.
âš™ï¸ 4. Suspense and loading.tsx in Next.js â€“ Full Explanation
ğŸ”„ The Problem It Solves:

When you're rendering a page that fetches data on the server, or lazily loads components, it can take time. You donâ€™t want a blank screen while it loads.

Next.js solves this by:

    Automatically wrapping your pages/layouts in a React Suspense boundary

    Showing a loading.tsx while the data/code is still loading

ğŸ’¡ Basic Rule:

If your route has async work (e.g. Prisma calls) and takes time to resolve, â¡ï¸ Next.js will automatically look for and render a loading.tsx file in the same folder.
ğŸ§  Example: Folder Structure

app/
â”œâ”€â”€ dashboard/
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ page.tsx          # Server component with async prisma fetch
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ loading.tsx       # Shown while page.tsx is loading

ğŸ§µ What Happens:

    User visits /dashboard

    dashboard/page.tsx fetches articles with Prisma (server-side)

    While it's fetching: âœ… dashboard/loading.tsx is rendered

    Once data arrives: âœ… dashboard/page.tsx replaces the loading screen

ğŸ’» Code Example
app/dashboard/page.tsx

import { prisma } from "@/lib/prisma"

const DashboardPage = async () => {
  const articles = await prisma.articles.findMany()
  return <div>Loaded Dashboard with {articles.length} articles</div>
}

export default DashboardPage

app/dashboard/loading.tsx

const Loading = () => {
  return <div className="p-4 text-gray-500">Loading dashboard...</div>
}

export default Loading

Result:

    While the articles are being fetched, the Loading component is shown.

âš™ï¸ Bonus: useTransition + Suspense (on client side)

Sometimes you want to defer rendering something on the client side while a transition is happening.
âœ¨ useTransition lets you mark state updates as low priority

const [isPending, startTransition] = useTransition()

<Button
  onClick={() =>
    startTransition(() => {
      router.push("/dashboard")
    })
  }
>
  Go to Dashboard
</Button>

â³ Combine with <Suspense>:

You can also wrap slow-loading components with Suspense:

<Suspense fallback={<Loading />}>
  <SomeComponentThatTakesTime />
</Suspense>

But you usually only need this manually for client-side lazy components. Server components already benefit from loading.tsx.
âœ… Summary
Feature	What it Does	Where it's Used
loading.tsx	Auto fallback UI while server page/layout is loading	Same folder as page.tsx or layout.tsx
useTransition	Defers state updates / navigation	Client components
<Suspense>	Shows a fallback during async/lazy loading	Often for client lazy imports
